    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix DRB scheduling priority inversion in MAC scheduler\n\n### Summary\nThere is a scheduling priority inversion where lower-priority traffic is served before higher-priority downstream of function `add_drb_am` in `openair2/LAYER2/nr_rlc/nr_rlc_oai_api.c`. This causes incorrect QoS handling where high-priority DRBs are not being scheduled appropriately.\n\n### Root Cause\nIn `process_addmod_bearers_cellGroupConfig()` function in `openair2/LAYER2/NR_MAC_gNB/gNB_scheduler_primitives.c`, when DRBs are added, the priority field in `nr_lc_config_t` structure is not being set from the RLC bearer configuration. This causes DRBs to default to priority 0 (highest priority) instead of their configured priority values, leading to incorrect scheduling order.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/LAYER2/NR_MAC_gNB/gNB_scheduler_primitives.c`: Added priority extraction logic in `process_addmod_bearers_cellGroupConfig()` to set DRB priorities from `mac_LogicalChannelConfig` when available.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure a UE with multiple DRBs having different priorities (e.g., DRB1 with priority 2, DRB2 with priority 10)\n2. Generate traffic for both DRBs simultaneously\n3. Observe that DRB2 (configured priority 10) gets scheduled before DRB1 (configured priority 2) due to the priority inversion\n4. Monitor scheduling logs to see that DRBs are being treated as priority 0 instead of their configured values\n\nThe fix ensures that DRBs are scheduled according to their configured logical channel priorities, resolving the priority inversion issue.\n"
}